18.title: Tests

19.body: those tests are just gwion (.gw) files, handling special comments: #! [skip] ( optionally followed by reason to skip) #! [todo] ( optionally followed by reason to delay testing) #! [contains] followed by string to match #! [excludes] followed by string not to match
19.title: Gwion tests

20.body:
those tests are just bash (.sh) files. they should start with this snippet #!/bin/bash
# [test] #5
n=0
[ "$1" ] && n="$1"
[ "$n" -eq 0 ] && n=1
source tests/sh/common.sh built with mdBook

40.title: Contributing

41.body: First off, thank you for considering translating gwion. Thanks to the build system, you're gonna get on tracks fast. Make your live easier use export TRANSLATION_TARGET=xxx so you don't have to repeat it on the command line
41.title: Contributing translations

42.body: You have to make sure there is a directory for your target language (e.g.: fr, en, es_ES ...). make translation-init TRANSLATION_TARGET=<xxx> Where <xxx> is your language of choice. It will fail if your language already exists, but this is not a problem.
42.breadcrumbs: Contributing » Step 1: Init the translation language
42.title: Step 1: Init the translation language

43.body: Next, you should adjust the translations. What about using your favorite editor? make translation-edit TRANSLATION_TARGET=<xxx>
43.title: Step 2: Edit

44.body: Maybe the sources changed, and there is more messages to translate? make translation-update This will update all languages. You can now get back to step 2 .
44.title: Step 3: Update

45.body:
It's now time to add your changes to the package make translation-commit TRANSLATION_TARGET=<xxx> In Gwion 's case, the vcs is the well known git , but the make recipe makes things simple Now please submit a pull request . built with mdBook
You'll find the source here, Luke!
45.title: Step 4: Add to VCS
